3:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Aevo calculates AVAX funding rates hourly using a time-weighted average price mechanism between the perpetual contract and spot reference price. The exchange's rollup architecture enables sub-second trade execution while maintaining on-chain settlement transparency. Funding payments occur every hour at the top of the clock, with rates typically ranging from -0.1% to +0.2% during normal market conditions. Aevo's off-chain order book provides deep liquidity aggregation while the rollup ensures deterministic funding rate calculations without MEV interference."}]
4:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","AVAX","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"AVAX exhibits volatile funding patterns during subnet launches, major DeFi protocol deployments, and validator staking events that create sustained directional pressure. The token's correlation with broader L1 performance metrics generates predictable funding divergences when Avalanche's ecosystem activity spikes relative to other chains. Aevo's pre-launch token market features often provide early AVAX derivative exposure that amplifies funding rate volatility."}]]}]
5:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical AVAX Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"AVAX funding rates on Aevo typically spike during Avalanche subnet launches and major ecosystem announcements, with rates reaching +0.5% during the Core blockchain integration and -0.3% during the FTX collapse period. The token shows distinct seasonal patterns around major DeFi summer periods and gaming subnet deployments. Funding rates tend to normalize within 24-48 hours of major news events, creating short-term arbitrage windows. Cross-exchange funding differentials often exceed 0.1% when Aevo's liquidity is concentrated compared to larger CEX platforms."}]]}]
6:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Rollup-Specific Arbitrage Opportunities"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Aevo's rollup architecture creates unique arbitrage scenarios when the sequencer processes large AVAX orders differently than mainnet DEXs. The exchange's options market integration generates additional funding pressure when AVAX call option volumes spike before major ecosystem events. Rollup finality delays can create temporary funding rate discrepancies lasting 10-15 minutes during high volatility periods. The platform's gas-free trading enables micro-arbitrage strategies that wouldn't be profitable on mainnet due to transaction costs."}]]}]
7:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Management Considerations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Aevo's rollup centralization presents withdrawal risks during extreme market stress, requiring careful position sizing relative to the sequencer's uptime history. The exchange's smaller liquidity pools can amplify slippage during large arbitrage position adjustments, particularly during AVAX's characteristically volatile sessions. Cross-collateral margin requirements may force liquidations when AVAX correlations with other held assets spike unexpectedly. The platform's options exposure can create additional Greeks risk when running delta-neutral funding strategies alongside existing option positions."}]]}]
8:["$","$Ld",null,{"items":[{"question":"How does Aevo's rollup affect AVAX funding rate calculations?","answer":"Aevo's rollup processes funding rate calculations deterministically every hour using on-chain price feeds, eliminating MEV interference that can skew rates on mainnet exchanges. The rollup's sub-second finality ensures precise timestamp-based funding computations that are more predictable than gas auction-dependent mainnet calculations."},{"question":"What makes AVAX funding rates unique on Aevo compared to CEXs?","answer":"Aevo's combined options and perpetuals orderbook creates additional funding pressure when AVAX option flows are heavy, as market makers hedge delta exposure through perpetuals. The exchange's pre-launch markets also enable AVAX derivative trading before major subnet launches, generating distinct funding patterns not available on traditional exchanges."},{"question":"How do AVAX subnet developments impact funding rates?","answer":"Major subnet launches typically drive positive funding rates as institutional flows lean long in anticipation of validator reward opportunities and ecosystem growth. Gaming and DeFi subnet announcements create the strongest funding spikes, often lasting 6-12 hours as market makers adjust hedges."},{"question":"What are the withdrawal considerations for AVAX arbitrage on Aevo?","answer":"Aevo requires rollup finalization for withdrawals, typically taking 2-4 hours during normal conditions but potentially longer during sequencer issues. Arbitrageurs should maintain sufficient capital on multiple exchanges to avoid forced position closures during withdrawal delays, particularly given AVAX's volatility."}]}]
